        <h2>Where Buildertrend excels for remodelers</h2>

        <h3>Selections management</h3>
        <p>Buildertrend's selections tool is a genuine differentiator for remodelers. You create a selections list for the project — tile options, cabinet finishes, plumbing fixtures, paint colors — and the homeowner reviews options, makes choices, and approves them digitally through the portal. Selections link to the budget so cost impacts of upgrades are visible at decision time. Approved selections feed purchase orders automatically.</p>

        <p>The practical impact: no more decisions made in the kitchen and forgotten, no more "I thought we decided on the tile" disputes. Every selection is documented with a timestamp and the homeowner's digital approval.</p>

        <h3>Client portal for homeowners</h3>
        <p>Buildertrend's homeowner portal is one of the best in the industry for residential work. Homeowners see their project timeline, view daily photos, get notified of upcoming schedule items, approve change orders, and communicate with the team through the portal — all from a clean mobile app. This level of transparency reduces client anxiety, reduces "status call" interruptions, and creates a professional image that supports premium pricing.</p>

        <h3>Change order capture</h3>
        <p>Remodeling change orders are frequent and often small — an extra outlet here, a different light fixture there, extra work discovered when opening a wall. Buildertrend makes generating, presenting, and getting approval on change orders fast enough that they actually get done. Change orders get presented to the homeowner through the portal with a description, cost, and e-signature button. This captures revenue that typically gets absorbed or forgotten.</p>

        <h3>Pricing for the remodeling business model</h3>
        <p>At $499/month flat, Buildertrend is accessible for remodelers doing $500K–$5M annually. Procore would cost 2–10x more for similar usage — a premium that doesn't buy remodeling-specific features, just commercial capabilities you won't use.</p>

        <h2>When Procore might make sense for a remodeler</h2>
        <p>There are specific situations where Procore is worth considering even for remodeling-oriented firms:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Remodelers doing commercial tenant improvement:</strong> If you regularly do commercial TI work in addition to residential remodeling, Procore's document management and commercial workflows may be worth the investment</li>
          <li><strong>High-volume, high-value remodelers:</strong> Companies doing $20M+ in annual residential remodeling with 30+ employees and complex document control needs occasionally find Procore's enterprise capabilities valuable</li>
          <li><strong>Design-build firms with significant architecture component:</strong> If you have in-house architects and operate more like a design firm than a contractor, Procore's BIM integration and design documentation tools may be relevant</li>
        </ul>

        <p>But these are edge cases. The typical remodeler doing $1M–$10M in residential renovation work doesn't need Procore's capabilities and will overpay for them.</p>

        <h2>What about Houzz Pro?</h2>
        <p>Houzz Pro deserves mention as a strong alternative specifically for remodelers. It has an excellent client experience, competitive pricing ($149–$399/month), and is particularly strong for designers and design-build remodelers. If you're a remodeler where design services are a significant component of the project, Houzz Pro's client visualization tools and portfolio management are worth evaluating alongside Buildertrend.</p>

